| Symptom | Root cause | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| ISI at `0x000E2B04` every run | `JitBlock& slot = cache[bkt]` reference was taken BEFORE `flushJitCache()`, which zeros `codePos` and clears all slots. The old reference still pointed to the same memory location. The block was then written at `codeBuf+0` but `slot.code` was set to `codeBuf+0` which on the next iteration appeared valid because `slot.valid` was still whatever garbage was in that cache entry from before — or alternatively the new block at position 0 was correctly written but then immediately evicted when the next compile call found the buffer nearly full again | `compile()` now re-derives `slot = cache[bkt]` by index AFTER the `flushJitCache()` call, ensuring the write always goes to the correct, freshly-cleared slot |
| GBA logo regression / no boot | Previous version excluded `pc < 4` from GBA valid range, which blocked the HLE BIOS entry at `0x00000000`. But the real problem was `isReady()` checking `pcData` which can be set before the memory map is fully wired, allowing `getActualPC()` to return 0 and `compile()` to build a block for address 0 using zeroed-out memory | `validPC` for GBA now explicitly excludes address 0 (`pc >= 4u`) so the HLE BIOS entry point always falls through to the interpreter; `isReady()` correctly uses `pcData != nullptr` which is only set by `flushPipeline()` inside `setPC()` inside `init()` |
