**The real answer**: `b` is not null, `b->nW > 0`, but `b->code` points to PPC instructions that themselves jump to `0x000E2B04`. This means the JIT compiled a block containing `emitExit(ctx, 0x000E2B04, EXIT_NORMAL)` where `nextPC = 0x000E2B04`, and `JitHelp_storeExit` stored it in `g_exitPC[1]`. Then the run loop called `interp.setPC(0x000E2B04)` — which is correct ARM behavior. But then `getActualPC()` returns `0x000E2B04 - 8 = 0x000E2AFC`, `isGoodPC(0x000E2AFC, true)` returns false, so `interpStep` is called. `interpStep` runs one opcode via the interpreter. Then `JitHelp_tick` fires. Then on the NEXT call to `runJitGba`, `interp.getActualPC()` is called again — and now the interpreter has advanced PC to some new address which IS in ROM and IS valid, so we compile and run fine.

The crash must be happening because `isGoodPC(exitPC, true)` is returning TRUE for `exitPC = 0x000E2B04`. Let's check: `validPC(0x000E2B04, gba=true)`: `pc = 0x000E2B04 & ~1 = 0x000E2B04`. Is `pc >= 4 && pc < 0x4000`? `0x000E2B04 < 0x4000`? `0x000E2B04 = 928516`. `0x4000 = 16384`. `928516 < 16384`? **NO**. Is it in EWRAM/IWRAM/ROM? No. So `validPC` returns false and `isGoodPC` returns false.

Then `interp.jitRunOpcode()` is called. This calls `runOpcode()`. But `setPC` was NOT called — because `isGoodPC` returned false, we went directly to `interp.jitRunOpcode()` without calling `setPC(exitPC)`. So the interpreter runs with whatever PC it had BEFORE the JIT block executed. The JIT block ran, modified `registers[r0..r14]` and CPSR via `JitHelp_syncTo`, but did NOT update `*registers[15]` (PC). So the interpreter re-executes the same instruction that the JIT just executed — creating an infinite loop that eventually produces wrong state, jumps to `0x000E2B04` through the HLE path, and crashes.

**The fix**: when `isGoodPC(exitPC)` is false AND reason is EXIT_NORMAL, we must still call `setPC(exitPC)` to let the interpreter handle it — because a bad-looking PC might be a valid HLE BIOS entry point. Only skip `setPC` if `exitPC` is completely nonsensical (0 or 0xFFFFFFFF). For EXIT_FALLBACK with a bad PC, something is deeply wrong and we should recover.

```cpp
// jit_ppc.cpp - only the run loops and validPC need to change
// Everything else stays identical to the previous version.

// ============================================================
// PC validity for JIT compilation only.
// A PC is "compilable" if it points into real mapped ROM/RAM.
// This is MORE restrictive than "valid ARM address" — HLE BIOS
// addresses like 0x000E2B04 are valid ARM addresses that the
// interpreter handles, but the JIT cannot compile them.
// ============================================================
static bool compilablePC(uint32_t pc, bool gba) {
    pc &= ~1u;
    if (gba) {
        // Exclude address 0 (HLE BIOS entry) and the entire
        // 0x0001..0x3FFF range (real BIOS ROM — not JIT-able
        // because we may be using HLE which has no ROM there).
        // Include only regions where the JIT can safely fetch opcodes.
        return (pc >= 0x02000000u && pc < 0x02040000u)   // EWRAM
            || (pc >= 0x03000000u && pc < 0x03008000u)   // IWRAM
            || (pc >= 0x08000000u && pc < 0x0E000000u);  // ROM
    }
    // NDS — ARM9 ITCM, main RAM, shared WRAM, ARM7 BIOS mirror
    return (pc < 0x4000u)
        || (pc >= 0x02000000u && pc < 0x02400000u)
        || (pc >= 0x03000000u && pc < 0x03800000u)
        || (pc >= 0xFFFF0000u);
}

// An exit PC is "handleable" if it is non-zero and non-sentinel.
// Even if it is not JIT-compilable (e.g. HLE BIOS address),
// it may be a valid ARM address the interpreter can execute.
// We must still call setPC() for these so the interpreter runs
// the right instruction.
static bool handleablePC(uint32_t pc) {
    return pc != 0u && pc != 0xFFFFFFFFu;
}

void runJitNds(Core& core) {
    for (int cpu = 0; cpu < 2; cpu++) {
        Interpreter& interp = core.interpreter[cpu];
        if (interp.halted) continue;

        if (!interp.isReady()) { interp.jitRunOpcode(); continue; }

        uint32_t pc = interp.getActualPC();

        // Only attempt JIT if we can actually compile this PC.
        // Non-compilable PCs (HLE regions, unmapped) go straight
        // to the interpreter which knows how to handle them.
        if (!compilablePC(pc, false)) { interp.jitRunOpcode(); continue; }

        JitBlock* b = compile(&interp, &core, pc, cpu == 1, cpu);
        if (!b || b->nW == 0) { interp.jitRunOpcode(); continue; }

        uint32_t* code = b->code;
        executeBlock_asm(code);

        uint32_t exitPC = g_exitPC[cpu];
        int      reason = g_exitReason[cpu];

        // Always call setPC if the exit PC is any real ARM address,
        // even if it is not JIT-compilable (e.g. falls into HLE BIOS).
        // The interpreter will then handle the non-compilable region.
        if (!handleablePC(exitPC)) {
            // Completely bogus exit PC — let interpreter recover
            interp.jitRunOpcode();
            continue;
        }

        interp.setPC(exitPC);
        if (reason == EXIT_FALLBACK) {
            interp.jitRunOpcode();
        }
    }
    JitHelp_tick(&core);
}

void runJitGba(Core& core) {
    Interpreter& interp = core.interpreter[1];
    if (interp.halted) { JitHelp_tick(&core); return; }

    if (!interp.isReady()) {
        interp.jitRunOpcode(); JitHelp_tick(&core); return;
    }

    uint32_t pc = interp.getActualPC();

    if (!compilablePC(pc, true)) {
        // PC is in a non-JIT region (HLE BIOS, unmapped, etc.)
        // Run through interpreter which handles these correctly.
        interp.jitRunOpcode(); JitHelp_tick(&core); return;
    }

    JitBlock* b = compile(&interp, &core, pc, true, 1);
    if (!b || b->nW == 0) {
        interp.jitRunOpcode(); JitHelp_tick(&core); return;
    }

    uint32_t* code = b->code;
    executeBlock_asm(code);

    uint32_t exitPC = g_exitPC[1];
    int      reason = g_exitReason[1];

    if (!handleablePC(exitPC)) {
        // Bogus exit — recover via interpreter
        interp.jitRunOpcode();
    } else {
        // Set PC unconditionally — even HLE BIOS addresses are
        // valid ARM destinations that setPC + interpreter handle.
        interp.setPC(exitPC);
        if (reason == EXIT_FALLBACK) {
            interp.jitRunOpcode();
        }
    }

    JitHelp_tick(&core);
}
